From: Adriel Santos <adriel@adriel.eu>
Subject: [PATCH] nss: an8855: make user ports flood targets by default (layered after 999-2757)

Fixes the dead standalone port of issue #5 at its real root.

an8855_setup() cleared every user port out of the BCF/UNUF/UNMF/UNIPMF
flood masks; only a bridge join (BR_FLOOD & co via .port_bridge_flags)
ever set them. A standalone port therefore was never a flood target -
and since standalone ports run with hardware learning disabled (SA_DIS)
and assisted learning only produces CPU-side entries, every
CPU-to-port frame on the tag_8021q build is flood-class: ARP requests
(broadcast, BCF) and replies to unlearned peers (unknown unicast,
UNUF). Result: the egress direction of a standalone port is completely
dead from a clean boot - "ARP from the wire is received and replied to
but the replies never reach the wire" - while ingress toward the CPU
keeps working (the CPU bits are set). The MTK-tag build never noticed:
its CPU TX uses the special tag's forced-port path, which bypasses the
flood/FDB lookup entirely.

This is why the issue #5 heal (bridge join/leave cycle) "worked": the
join applied BR_FLOOD and set the port's flood bits, and nothing on
leave cleared them again. The tag_8021q VLAN reprogramming that the
heal also performed was coincidental - register dumps show the VLAN
table, port matrix, PVID/PVC and host FDB are all correct before the
heal. The conduit move was a red herring for the same reason: any
standalone user port fails identically on either CPU port. (A second,
lesser artifact discovered on the way: dsa_port_change_conduit() makes
the port inherit the new conduit's MAC, so peers with the old MAC
cached black-hole their replies until they re-ARP - an upstream DSA
behavior, not a driver bug.)

Default the user-port flood bits ON instead. This matches the DSA core
contract - dsa_port_clear_brport_flags() restores flood ON when a port
leaves a bridge, and on join the BR_* flags are applied right after, so
admin-controlled flood on bridge ports keeps working. The later UNMF
write for the CPU ports becomes set-bits so it no longer clobbers the
user-port bits.

Empirical proof (clean boot, standalone lan4 on conduit eth0, peer
behind the port): before - port dead, UNUF/BCF/UNMF/UNIPMF all show the
port's bit clear, switch MIB shows no egress; after a bridge join/leave
- the same registers show the bit set and traffic flows with zero other
register changes. With this patch the flood bits are correct from
setup and the port works from the first boot, no heal needed. The
99-heal-wan-conduit hotplug workaround is removed with this fix.

Link: https://github.com/ADCDS/openwrt-xiaomi-ax3000t-rd03v2/issues/5
--- a/drivers/net/dsa/an8855.c
+++ b/drivers/net/dsa/an8855.c
@@ -2086,22 +2086,33 @@
 		if (ret)
 			return ret;
 
-		/* Disable Broadcast Forward on user ports */
-		ret = regmap_clear_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_BCF, BIT(dp->index));
+		/* tag_8021q: user ports must be flood TARGETS by default. A
+		 * standalone port has hardware learning disabled (SA_DIS) and
+		 * assisted learning only covers CPU-side entries, so every
+		 * CPU-to-port frame - ARP requests and replies to unlearned
+		 * peers first of all - is flood-class; with the port excluded
+		 * from BCF/UNUF/UNMF the egress direction is completely dead
+		 * (issue #5). This also matches the DSA core contract: on
+		 * bridge leave dsa_port_clear_brport_flags() restores flood
+		 * ON, and on bridge join the BR_* flags are applied right
+		 * after, so an admin-disabled flood on a bridge port still
+		 * takes effect via .port_bridge_flags. The MTK-tag build
+		 * never noticed because its CPU TX uses the special tag's
+		 * forced-port path, which bypasses the flood/FDB lookup.
+		 */
+		ret = regmap_set_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_BCF, BIT(dp->index));
 		if (ret)
 			return ret;
 
-		/* Disable Unknown Unicast Forward on user ports */
-		ret = regmap_clear_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNUF, BIT(dp->index));
+		ret = regmap_set_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNUF, BIT(dp->index));
 		if (ret)
 			return ret;
 
-		/* Disable Unknown Multicast Forward on user ports */
-		ret = regmap_clear_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNMF, BIT(dp->index));
+		ret = regmap_set_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNMF, BIT(dp->index));
 		if (ret)
 			return ret;
 
-		ret = regmap_clear_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNIPMF, BIT(dp->index));
+		ret = regmap_set_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNIPMF, BIT(dp->index));
 		if (ret)
 			return ret;
 
@@ -2125,8 +2136,10 @@
 	if (ret)
 		return ret;
 
-	/* Unknown multicast frame forwarding to the cpu port(s) */
-	ret = regmap_write(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNMF, dsa_cpu_ports(ds));
+	/* Unknown multicast frame forwarding to the cpu port(s). Set-bits,
+	 * not a full write: the user-port flood bits set above must survive.
+	 */
+	ret = regmap_set_bits(priv->regmap, AN8855_UNMF, dsa_cpu_ports(ds));
 	if (ret)
 		return ret;
 
